'''Augustin Aimable Dumon-Dumortier''' (4 December 1791 &ndash; 28 January 1852) was a [[Belgium|Belgian]] [[industrialist]], [[diplomat]] and [[Liberalism|liberal]] [[politician]].

==Life and career==
Born at [[Lille]], he was [[List of Presidents of the Belgian Senate|President]] of the [[Belgian Senate]] from 27 June 1848 until 28 January 1852, [[governor]] of the province of [[Hainaut (province)|Hainaut]] and [[burgomaster]] of [[Tournai]]. In 1849, he was sent to the [[Netherlands]] as a special envoy to congratulate [[William III of the Netherlands|William III]] upon his [[coronation]]. This was 19 years after the [[Belgian Revolution]], which had made an end to the [[United Kingdom of the Netherlands]].

He was a ''chevalier de l'ordre de Leopold'', and he received the [[Netherlands|Dutch]] ''grand-croix de l'ordre de la Couronne de Chêne''.

Dumon-Dumortier died at [[Tournai]] in 1852.

== Honours ==
* 1849: Knight Grand Cross of the [[Order of the Oak Crown]].<ref>Handelsblad (Het) 19-04-1849</ref>

