'''Saeed Karimian''' (8 August 1972<ref name="youtube">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YrQWjXi2HxA|title=&#x202b;اطلاعیه شماره یک شبکه جم&#x202c;&lrm;|website=YouTube|accessdate=1 August 2017}}</ref> – 29 April 2017) was an [[Iran]]ian television executive, the founder, chairman, and owner of [[Dubai]]-based <ref name="National">{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/world/middle-east/iranian-media-group-chief-shot-dead-in-istanbul|title=Iranian media group chief shot dead in Istanbul|publisher=The National}}</ref>[[GEM TV]], which runs 17 [[Persian language|Persian-language]] TV channels, plus one each in [[Kurdish language|Kurdish]], [[Azeri language|Azeri]], and [[Arabic]].<ref name="The Guardian1">{{cite web|author=Reuters |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/apr/30/iranian-gem-tv-saeed-karimian-shot-dead-in-istanbul-turkish-media-reports |title=Iranian TV executive shot dead in Istanbul, Turkish media reports &#124; World news |publisher=The Guardian |date=30 April 2017 |accessdate=30 April 2017}}</ref><ref name="BBC1">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-39761451 |title=Gem TV: Iranian CEO Saeed Karimian shot dead in Istanbul - BBC News |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date= 30 April 2017|accessdate=30 April 2017}}</ref> Karimian who was [[British nationality law|British national]]<ref name="Guardian">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/apr/30/iranian-gem-tv-saeed-karimian-shot-dead-in-istanbul-turkish-media-reports|title=Iranian TV executive shot dead in Istanbul, Turkish media report|publisher=The Guardian}}</ref> had been tried in absentia by a court in [[Tehran]], and sentenced to a prison term of six years for spreading propaganda against Iran.<ref name="BBC1"/>
Karimian was shot dead in [[Istanbul]], Turkey, on 29 April 2017, along with his Kuwaiti business partner.<ref name="The Guardian1"/><ref name="BBC1"/><ref name="Guardian" /> According to the exiled Iranian opposition group [[National Council of Resistance of Iran|National Council of Resistance]] Karimian was assassinated by the [[Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps|Revolutionary Guard]] on the orders of [[Ayatollah Ali Khamenei]], the country’s [[Supreme Leader of Iran|Supreme Leader]].<ref name="ddd">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/04/30/world/europe/saeed-karimian-iran-turkey-gem-tv.html?_r=0|title=Exiled Iranian TV Executive Is Assassinated in Istanbul|publisher=New York Times}}</ref> In May 2017, Turkish media reported that two people accused for the assassination of Karimian were arrested in Serbia with fake passports on their way to Iran. [http://fa.rfi.fr/%D9%85%D8%AA%D9%87%D9%85%D8%A7%D9%86-%D8%A8%D9%87-%D9%82%D8%AA%D9%84-%D8%B3%D8%B9%DB%8C%D8%AF-%DA%A9%D8%B1%DB%8C%D9%85%DB%8C%D8%A7%D9%86%D8%8C-%D9%85%D8%AF%DB%8C%D8%B1-%D8%B4%D8%A8%DA%A9%D9%87-%D8%AA%D9%84%D9%88%DB%8C%D8%B2%DB%8C%D9%88%D9%86%DB%8C-%D8%AC%D9%85-%D8%A8%D8%A7%D8%B2%D8%AF%D8%A7%D8%B4%D8%AA-%D8%B4%D8%AF%D9%86%D8%AF-20170518/%D8%A7%DB%8C%D8%B1%D8%A7%D9%86]
